Would a story about robots that are slowly becoming human work here?
I have an idea that some earth power creates sentient machines to win a war, and in exchange for their service are given flesh. As in they slowly begin to become human in the flesh.
However there were those who rejected mortality in meat but where already capable of both seeding and birthing life. These are cast off of earth on a "great expedition" where these outcasts are told to bring the humans they bear to new and fertile worlds and bring those with other sentients into the fold.

Our main character would be a middle-state human-machine where his arms and most of chest are flesh and blood, along with his lower jaw and digestive track.
He would be guarding a colony watching his friend's children play. He stares at his hands and has a breakdown. He's not a machine, the immortality he sought from it is lost, he's not a person, he has ever seen anything with the eyes he could've had.
He would leave the colony that night as he feels the metal around his toes lift signaling to him that his legs will join his arms in being flesh.
He goes into the woods that border the settlement and he walks for weeks, until he comes across another village, one not inhabited by humans, but rather strange humanoids with a mass of tentacles for a mouth and pillaresc heads while their arms seem to move as if they have no bones.
As he approaches one lashes out at him with an extra set of limbs connecting with his metal head doing nothing to it.
The squid person then scream-hisses and the others come out and surround him and he is taken prisoner-slave to them.
I don't know where I'd take if from here but I think it could be fun and I would rack "first longform squid story" under my belt
